{meta: title Old Porch Swing}
{meta: artist Gene Watson}
{meta: composer Joe Allen & Charlie Williams}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[C]Its hung there on the front porch
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
Since this old house was built
Its [G7]where the old men whittle
And the women fleece their [C]quilts
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
Its held four generations
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
Through whatever life could bring
That old [G7]swing  that old porch [C]swing
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 5}
[C]It held a grieving widow
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 6}
When my daddy's daddy died
And [G7]now it rocks my children
When they close their sleepy [C]eyes
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 7}
It's where I popped the question
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 8}
With a quarter karat ring
That old [G7]swing  that old porch [C7][C]swing 
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 9}
Its [F]been there through the sunshine 
Its [C]had its share of rain
Been a [D7]witness to some good times
And [G7]alike amount of pain
If [C]it could tell its story
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 10}
What a ballad it could sing
That old [G7]swing  that old porch [C]swing
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 11}
[C]It's where brother read the letter 
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 12}
That sent him off to war
We [G7]knew he had to go and fight
But we didn't know what [C]for
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 13}
When he came home he just sat there
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 14}
And never said a thing
In that [G7]swing  that old porch [C]swing
{end_of_verse}

